result.execSummary:
The defendant Nathan Edward Bolinger was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Possession of Narcotic Drugs, a class I felony, Wisconsin Statutes 961.41(3g)(am).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

supervisions.notes: Same conditions shall apply for extended supervision as imposed for probation.

miscConds.notes: lf extended supervision is revoked and the defendant will have a mandatory release from prison, a civil judgment shall be entered for the balance due.

Defendant shall participate in all counseling, assessments, and/or treatment programs directed by the probation agent, including an AODA assessment and shall follow through with all treatment recommendations. 

Defendant shall maintain absolute sobriety. 

Defendant shall provide a biological specimen for DNA analysis.  Defendant has the right to request expungement of DNA analysis in writing through the Department of Justice.
Defendant shall not possess or consume any controlled substances without a valid prescription.
Defendant shall obtain and maintain full time employment or full time school status, or a combination of employment and school equal to full time status.

Prosecuting Attorney Allison E. Cogbill in court for the State of Wisconsin.  Defendant appears via video in custody from the Washington County Jail without counsel.  Court has colloquy with Defendant regarding right to be physically present at today's hearing and accepts consent to use of video conferencing.  Defendant referred to State Public Defender.  State requests cash bond.  $1,000 cash bond set.  Case passed.  Case recalled.  Per Officer Vargo, defendant refuses to cooperate.  Court notes that after bond was set, defendant became uncooperative and belligerent.  Court schedules preliminary hearing.  Jail security given a slip for the State Public Defender information to provide to defendant.   Preliminary hearing scheduled for July 22, 2022 at 09:00 am.
